segments.text: Not the top 10, not top 5 or 10.
But top 20, 25%.
And what is impressive about that is that when you look at the top 10 or 15, they've been around forever.
And this new college made those quantum leaps.
And I attribute that to the leadership of those two deans, Hubert and then Corrigan, and the faculty.
Because the faculty came in just running right off the bat.
And they started getting recognition in publishing and in research.
And we got recognition very quickly.
Who are some of those star faculty members that are worthy of note?
Well, I think in the area of children's literature, Donna Norton certainly stands out.
Donna Norton is probably the number one
figure in children's literature in the country.
Bill Rupley and Mark Sadowski are probably two of the leading researchers and publishers in the field of reading.
We've had some highly successful research and grants people in math education and science education.
You're talking about the college now?
Mm-hmm.
Okay, in the college?
Well, certainly, I can't think of one of the names in Ed Syke that came out of...
He'd been at the University of Nebraska and came into Ed Syke, but he was a very prominent...
person in that whole field of educational psychology for life.
I can't think of his name right now.
Jim McNamara had established himself nationally in educational statistics, was well recognized in that field.
Statewide, probably the
early people that would be recognized would have been because of their educational administration type background.
You know, the Frank Huberts, the Paul Henslings, the Les Richardsons.

Carl Landis and his whole effort over in that field with the human resource research that they were doing, particularly in the field of smoking, they were, they don't get, I think, they don't get enough recognition.
They were pioneers.
They were the early pioneers in identifying
the hazards of smoking.
I can remember that when I first came to Texas A&M.
So we're talking about 1969, 1970, these guys were way, way ahead of the game.
Are there some opportunities that in hindsight, are there some opportunities that we missed?
You know clarity of looking backward or if we had known then what we know now we would have done this or that.
All right.
Let me ask a different way.
Can you think of any individual that we lost or that we didn't get that we might have gotten or might have kept.
I can't, Haskell.
Now, when you talk to other department heads in other departments, you might find that.
One of the things that I came away with in that role were the number of people I didn't want coming to Texas A&M that I would encounter.
I remember the year that
I mentioned I hired Jack Campbell because my interview with him up at Chicago, Illinois during a national convention.
I had one fellow come in there that was with the University of California, and he really wanted that job.
And he only wanted five students, one seminar, and about $15,000 more than I was offering.
Well, I didn't want that type person at all.
And you would run into a lot of people that you interviewed like that, because they were kind of prima donnas.
They just wanted five students, five doctoral students, and a lot of money, and just leave me alone type thing.
We were developing.
Yeah, we needed workers.
We needed people that understood what the real world of work was in education.
Did you and your colleagues in these years, did you all think that progress was being made?
Yes, I think so.
I think there was, especially in those early years, there was a great cohesiveness.
We used to go to Savisa and have lunch together and just continue our conversations that may have started at a faculty meeting.
We just continued them out there in the lunch hour.
A lot of cohesiveness.
Now, you moved from the fourth floor, was the fourth floor of academic?
Yes.
To?
Third floor of academic.
Third floor, and then?
And then by that time the new Harrington Building had opened and we moved over to the Harrington Building.
And that's where you were until you retired?
Yes.
Peggy Ritchie and I go back a long way.
Describe her as the key person in the dean's office.
Well, she was extremely dependable, courteous.
You just loved Peggy Ritchie.
If you wanted a secretary in a dean's office, you wouldn't go beyond Peggy Ritchie.

just just a gem very informative she's very knowledgeable she knew what was going on and again I think Dean Hubert relied on her a lot and felt comfortable giving her responsibilities as a secretary head secretary and I can't imagine her ever overstepping her appropriate responsibility

never i don't think i ever heard her say uh... bad word and negative or have a negative comment about anyone but i also can't imagine anybody being able to put one over on her because she was pretty uh... pretty savvy and pretty pretty uh... clear-headed uh... let's see do you remember uh... anywhere in uh... the department of the country do you remember anytime where there was just some
real snafu.
Well, I don't know.
When you say snafu, you mean where things didn't jive?
Yeah, yeah.
They were completely off balance.
Yeah, about, I'm going to say about 20 years into the College of Education, the fragmenting began to emerge.
And I think that maybe that happens

after you get a faculty that's been established and they're moving along with their program and new faculty are coming in with new ideas and they want their kind of program, you know, to emerge and you begin to get kind of a clash here.
I would describe it this way, probably the first 20 years it was
department within a college and all of our effort was toward the students.
The fragmented segment started when numbers of new faculty or faculty after a few years wanted specialization

you know don't get me involved with those other people this is my field very narrow that's right and and of course they do good things you know if you're looking for specialization they have really specialized and can tell you the the finer things of whatever they've specialized in but
There's a trade-off.
When you go that deep into specialization, you lose track of what the overall mission and the overall picture is.
And when we celebrated our 30th College of Education 30th anniversary, I took the lead in writing up the history on the Department of Curriculum Instruction, Educational Curriculum Instruction.
And when I finished, I finished with the words, quo vadis, wherefore goest thou?
Because I think that's what happens.
People begin to lose, what's the mission?
What are the objectives?
How do we work together to get there?
And you get fragmented things going on.
Now, I'm not going to ask you the negative.
Who were your favorite colleagues?
Oh, there were so many.
Gosh.
Short time that he was there, Jerry Salick, because we were involved from the very beginning with trying to get new programs started.
He left, went up to New Mexico.
David David, Bob Schutz, just really top-flight people.
Jack Campbell, a wonderful guy.
The new faculty that came in, like the Donna Nortons and the Bill Rupleys and the Donna Wisemans
Sadowskis and the Patlarks and so forth.
Just really fine, fine people.
In more recent years, I only knew him for a short period because I retired, but Charlie Lamb came into math education out of the university.
He'd been an associate professor over at UT Austin and came over, joined us as a full professor in math education.
Just really fine.

Because I had been department head, I was associating with people out in the other departments, and I just found people like Jim Boone and Carl Landis and Leonard Ponder and all of those department heads and people were
were really good people.
I think Corrigan and Hubert both had done a good job in selecting people to assume responsibilities in those roles and enjoyed working with them.
They were easy to work with, just easy to work with.
You mentioned continuing conversations from the department on over to lunch at Sabisa.
Yes.
When did that start?
When did that begin?
Almost immediately, yeah.
And how many years did it go on?
Probably a good ten years.

I would say this first signs of fragmenting didn't come in until maybe... See, Bob Schutz was department head for ten years, and I would say only the last couple of years where all of us began to see it.
But I'd say, you know, my time and seven, eight years under Bob's time, there was a very cohesive group.
And as I say, the fragmented people, the people that I associated with that fragmentation, didn't want to do that.
They weren't.
interested in having lunch.
I think they were more interested in pursuing their their own specialization or whatever, you know.
I always worry if those people fall within what I call the missionary complex.

By that I mean the person who feels that he or she is doing us a favor by being here, that they've come from a superior civilization, that we're behind the times, and they're going to be here doing missionary service, and then they will return and leave us peasants.
And I always worry about that.
I think there's some truth to that.
Now, we've had a couple people like that who have
kind of come in with that attitude and have left, but have come back.
Oh, good, good, good.
And said, this is where I want to be.
But apparently, for whatever reason, they had to experience that.

They had to go through this missionary approach and saying, you know, we're coming out of a program that's above you, et cetera, et cetera, and I'm going back there, only to find out that when they got back there, that wasn't.
what it looked like when they had been a student or whatever.
And now they wanted to come back.
And they were leaving tenured positions elsewhere, pretty good positions, just to come back.
Now you served how many years here?
Thirty.
I was here thirty years.
Thirty years, exactly.
Do you have any advice on this?
I've just appointed you as the consultant.
Do you have any advice for the College of Education today?
I would really like to see them come back to spending more of a
informal, camaraderie kind of building an atmosphere of cohesiveness again, like we had those first 15, 20 years, where we really did have a mission we understood and goals to be accomplished.
And we're not afraid to be innovative and experimental, if you want to call it.
Because I think in education today, we're kind of faltering all across the country.
And what worked 20 years ago is still there.
And that's not the case.
Things have changed.
I think there are some signs of spurts.
Although I'm only getting it from the outside now because I've been away for three years.
But I'm beginning to see signs where they're, for example, this whole thrust with the internet and technology.
I'm seeing and hearing comments by people out of the College of Education that maybe they are locking into that and recognizing that this thing is going to be huge.
and it's going to impact education at all levels.
I don't care if it's
pre-school years to doctoral program years.
The internet and technology are going to just have a tremendous impact.
And I think all the research and grantsmanship that's going on out there now to get into that ballpark.
And they're having some success.
They're hitting on some million-dollar grants out there now in that field.
So I'm glad to see that.
But they're going to have to work at how do you rally then the rest, the whole, to get behind this as a mission or a goal or objective type of thing.
That would be an undertaking.
Are there some other schools in education nationally that have made similar kinds of rapid progress?
None really come to my mind, Haskell.
All the time that I was active out there and even being out of the scene now for three years, I don't see the rapid growth
the rapid impact that our colleagues seem to have in such a short period of time.
So that in the big leagues, the University of Texas at Austin and us, is there anybody else in Texas you'd put in that big league?
Not in Texas.
What about in the Southwest?
States around us?
I guess you'd have to include LSU.
Okay.
But other than that, I'm just not willing to put any of them in there.
Oklahoma, Oklahoma State, I'm not ready to, uh-uh.
Alabama, all of those.
I don't think so.
All right, let's see.
I'm getting close to the end of the thoughts that I had.
Are there some topics that we've not touched on that you wanted to be sure?
You've done a pretty thorough job.
In fact, you've raised a lot of questions that I would not have even thought to ask about.
And of course, without catalogs and so forth, there were

things that i'm sure i've overlooked are there some people that that we haven't mentioned that if you if they could be here today that you'd want to thank well um all the people i've mentioned yeah but in addition to any that we haven't mentioned did i mention don barker yes yeah certainly uh don oh my
Okay, well, all right.
Two other things before the last question.
One is, if you have any A&M related...

uh paraphernalia materials pictures and so forth that at some point you are want to get rid of i beg you please pass it on to the a m archives it'll be safer there than any other place that's good and then the the next last question is let's make believe that someone came up to you and handed you a check for a million dollars
and there was only one requirement.
You had to pass it on to Texas A&M, but you could decide how it was spent.
What would you tell A&M to do with it?
In other words, what are your keenest interests at A&M?
I think I'd almost go with scholarships.
For whom?
Well, coming out of education, I wanted to go to the College of Education.
Undergraduates, graduates, rich, poor, special major?
I think I would want to go to...
the graduate level in this whole field of educational technology because I still see that as the area that really needs to be tapped in a big way, that they need to really jump into
You know, full force.
I think the others will continue.
All the other programs, I think, will continue.
Reading, math, education, science, ed administration, educational psychology, et cetera.
But unless they can latch on to that one, I think somebody is going to take the lead, and they're going to run off with that.

And we would have a chance, I think, since we're now a pretty well-established college, that if we started really making that a high top priority, we could become one of the leading colleges of education just because of that.
Last question.
What feelings are in your heart for Texas A&M now?
Only the dearest.
I love Texas A&M University.
I think all of their traditions and the students, I think the students still continue to be, for the most part, what I saw the first 10 years or so that I spent here.
And they're kind of the heart and soul of Texas A&M University.
Let's quit there.
Thank you.
